\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Genesis edge-push benchmark across material families.} Rendered frames from the Genesis MPM simulator after the pile has settled on the source platform. Scene geometry (Franka Panda, source platform, target bin, particle pile placement following Config~D, 5.5\,cm from the open edge) is identical across panels; only the MPM material parameters differ (overlaid bottom-right of each panel: Young's modulus $E$ in Pa, Poisson ratio $\nu $, density $\rho $ in kg\,m$^{-3}$). Equilibrium shapes are visibly distinct---granular sand spreads, cohesive snow holds together loosely, and the elastoplastic medium retains a tight rebounded block. Bottom-left (green) tag reports the scripted-controller transfer efficiency for that material as a discriminative-difficulty reference. Particle surface colours are chosen per panel for visual contrast and have no effect on dynamics.}}{5}{figure.caption.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:scene_schematic}{{2}{5}{\textbf {Genesis edge-push benchmark across material families.} Rendered frames from the Genesis MPM simulator after the pile has settled on the source platform. Scene geometry (Franka Panda, source platform, target bin, particle pile placement following Config~D, 5.5\,cm from the open edge) is identical across panels; only the MPM material parameters differ (overlaid bottom-right of each panel: Young's modulus $E$ in Pa, Poisson ratio $\nu $, density $\rho $ in kg\,m$^{-3}$). Equilibrium shapes are visibly distinct---granular sand spreads, cohesive snow holds together loosely, and the elastoplastic medium retains a tight rebounded block. Bottom-left (green) tag reports the scripted-controller transfer efficiency for that material as a discriminative-difficulty reference. Particle surface colours are chosen per panel for visual contrast and have no effect on dynamics}{figure.caption.2}{}}
\newlabel{fig:scene_schematic@cref}{{[figure][2][]2}{[1][4][]5}{}{}{}}
